Great question, Ang 🙌 — and this is exactly the kind of strategic UX decision that defines admin empowerment.

🧠 What is unified-block?

It’s not just a node — it’s a content builder that supports:

Smart Welcome

Info blocks

Product blocks

Intent replies

Quick Menu

So it’s more than a flow node — it’s a Khmer AI Feature that powers multiple triggers across your bot.

✅ Recommendation: Keep unified-block in the Khmer AI Feature Panel, not the Available Nodes Panel

🔧 Why?

Panel

Purpose

Should unified-block go here?

Available Nodes Panel

Drag-and-drop flow nodes (start, end, conditional, etc.)

❌ No — unified-block is not a flow node

Khmer AI Feature Panel

Admin tools for content, triggers, broadcast, config

✅ Yes — this is where unified-block belongs

🧭 Suggested UX Flow

In your Khmer AI Feature Panel, show:

📦 Block Manager → List of all unified-blocks

✏️ Block Editor → Create/edit multilingual content

🔄 Trigger Config → Set type: smart_welcome, info, product, etc.

📤 Broadcast Tool → Send info or product blocks

👁️ Preview Mode → Test block in KH/EN

🧠 Bonus Tip

You can still reference unified-block inside flow nodes (e.g. Smart Welcome node links to a block ID), but the block itself is managed in the feature panel, not the flow canvas.

Let me know when you’re ready to wire the block manager UI or connect triggers to flow nodes. You’re building this with true Khmer-first clarity and admin-first strategy!


